More than 58 percent of the world's coral reefs are endangered due to pollution, over-harvesting of reef fish, and other human factors, as reported by the World Conservation Union (IUCN).
The destruction of reefs will impact over one billion lives, with climate change and introduced species like starfish exacerbating the situation.
The IUCN plans to release a detailed report on coral reefs globally, highlighting the urgent need for conservation efforts.
Despite some reefs recovering from past damage, the overall outlook remains grim, with only 30 percent of coral reefs currently healthy.
The pressing environmental issue of reef degradation requires immediate action to prevent further irreversible
